 Overcurrent Protection & Relay Coordination Fundamentals
Objective:

Develop a clear understanding of overcurrent protection logic, including the roles of CTs, relays, and circuit breakers, and begin practical relay setting design.

System Context:
Modeled a simple LV distribution system in ETAP:

Grid → Transformer (1 MVA, 33/0.415 kV)
LV Bus → Cable → Lump Load (0.75 MVA)
Protection: Circuit Breaker (CB1) + CT + Overcurrent Relay (OCR)

Key Concepts Learned:
1. Protection System Architecture
CT (Current Transformer):
Steps down high current (e.g., 1500 A → 5 A)
Provides safe, scaled input to relay
Relay (OCR):
Processes current signal from CT
Applies logic:
Pickup threshold
Time delay
Instantaneous trip
Determines when to trip
Circuit Breaker (CB):
Executes relay command
Physically interrupts fault current

2. Protection Logic (Core Insight)
Protection is not about components — it is about decision timing
Normal Load (~1043 A)	No trip
Overload (~1200–2000 A)	Delayed trip
Fault (>8000 A)	Instant trip

3. Full Load Current Calculation
Calculated load current:
I = (S/(√3 x V))
Result:
1043 A

4. Relay Setting Design (Engineering-Based)
Pickup Current:
Set at ~1.1–1.2 × FLC
Selected: 1200 A
Instantaneous Trip:
Based on fault level margin
Selected range: 8000 – 12000 A

5. Critical Design Insight
Instantaneous setting must NOT be too low
→ Prevents nuisance tripping during overload conditions

6. ETAP Limitation Encountered
Relay curve libraries (IEC/IEEE) not available
Unable to generate standard inverse TCC curves
Adapted by focusing on:
Logical protection behavior
Manual setting interpretation

Challenges Faced:
Difficulty linking CT → Relay → CB properly
Missing relay curve dropdown (library limitation)
Misinterpretation of primary vs secondary current scaling
Initial misunderstanding of pickup = 0 impact

Breakthrough Moment:
Transitioned from “trying to make ETAP work”
to
Understanding protection system behavior independent of software

Key Takeaway:

Protection design is about system behavior and coordination, not software output.

Protection Coordination (New Insight)
Introduced selectivity principle
Designed time coordination between:
Downstream breaker (CB1)
Upstream breaker (CB2)

Applied grading margin:
T upstream =T downstream +0.3 to 0.5 sec

Ensured:
Local fault isolation
System stability
Minimal outage impact

Backup Protection & Mis-coordination Insight;
Understood role of backup protection (CB2)
Designed coordination such that:
CB1 clears local faults
CB2 operates only on delay or upstream faults
Identified risk of instantaneous mis-setting:
Too low → upstream breaker trips first
Leads to loss of selectivity
